  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing Cabernet Sauvignon with grilled versus braised meats?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled meats develop caramelized, smoky flavors that echo Cabernet Sauvignon's oak aging and concentrated fruit, creating harmonious flavor bridges. Braised meats, cooked slowly in liquid, become tender and develop rich, complex flavors that complement the wine's earthy undertones and softer tannin structure. Both cooking methods work excellently, but grilled meats emphasize the wine's power while braised dishes highlight its elegance.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Cabernet Sauvignon good for beginners to pair with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Cabernet Sauvignon is actually excellent for beginners learning food pairing because it follows clear, predictable rules: pair with rich, savory foods and avoid delicate dishes. The wine's bold character makes successful pairings obvious and forgiving, unlike subtle wines where nuances matter more. Start with classic combinations like steak or aged cheese to build confidence before exploring more creative pairings.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What vegetarian dishes pair well with Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rich, umami-driven vegetarian dishes like mushroom risotto, eggplant parmesan, or grilled portobello mushrooms provide enough depth and savory intensity to complement Cabernet Sauvignon's bold character. Dishes with roasted vegetables, especially root vegetables with caramelized edges, also work well. The key is choosing preparations that are substantial and flavorful rather than light and fresh.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does the age of Cabernet Sauvignon affect food pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young Cabernet Sauvignons with more aggressive tannins pair best with fatty, protein-rich foods like ribeye steak or lamb, which help soften the wine's astringency. Aged Cabernet Sauvignons develop more complex, earthy flavors and smoother tannins, making them suitable for more refined dishes like duck confit or mushroom-based preparations. The wine's evolution allows for increasingly sophisticated pairing opportunities as it matures.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing food with Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing foods that are too light or delicate, leaving the wine to dominate and taste harsh or overpowering. Many people also serve the wine too warm, which amplifies the alcohol and makes it harder to pair successfully with food. Always ensure your dishes have enough richness and intensity to stand up to Cabernet Sauvignon's bold personality.</p>
